  "market_context": "Bearish market structure on EURUSD 1H chart with defined trading range (1.16800–1.17800), recent equal highs near 1.17200, and a bullish FVG forming above the range, creating a supply-demand conflict.",
  "key_observation": "Price formed equal highs at ~1.17200 (liquidity zone), a fair value gap (FVG) above the trading range, and a supply zone from the last bullish candle; bearish control resumed after price failed to break above the protected high.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify bearish market structure on EURUSD 1H and define the latest trading range from swing low (1.16800) to swing high (1.17800).",
    "Step 2: Mark the protected high at ~1.17200 (aligned with 'Bos' label) as a key liquidity area and potential reversal point.",
    "Step 3: Identify two potential supply zones: the candle that created the FVG and the last bullish momentum candle before the bearish impulse move.",
    "Step 4: Note the formation of equal highs near 1.17200, indicating a liquidity pool from sellers’ stop-losses and breakout traders’ buy stops.",
    "Step 5: Observe the bullish FVG as a sign of strong demand, creating a supply vs. demand conflict; confirm bearish dominance when price rejected above the protected high and broke below the FVG zone.",
    "Step 6: Zoom into 15-minute chart to refine entry: mark the FVG candle’s body (1.17200–1.17400) as the supply zone for short entries.",
    "Step 7: Execute short trade with entry at 1.17300, stop loss at 1.17050, and trail stop to each new protected high after downside breakouts.",
    "Step 8: Achieve ~1:4 risk-to-reward by trailing stop through multiple break-of-structure moves until reversal."
  ],
  "outcome": "Successful short trade with ~1:4 risk-to-reward ratio using trailing stop after multiple downside breakouts.",
  "lessons": "Combine HTF structure (trading range, equal highs, protected high) with LTF entry (FVG-based supply zone) and dynamic risk management (trailing stop after BOS) to maximize reward while protecting profits.",
